279
00:16:25,588 --> 00:16:28,228
This example, and the last one with the tree,

280
00:16:28,228 --> 00:16:30,526
these are both very visual programs;

281
00:16:30,526 --> 00:16:32,996
we're able to see our changes just by seeing how the picture changes.

282
00:16:32,996 --> 00:16:37,734
So I was thinking about, how we could do more abstract coding

283
00:16:37,734 --> 00:16:39,146
that's more in line with this principle.

284
00:16:39,146 --> 00:16:44,407
How can we write a generic algorithm in such a way that we can see what we're doing.

285
00:16:44,407 --> 00:16:48,578
So as an example, let's take a look at binary search.

286
00:16:48,578 --> 00:16:51,615
Super quick refresher on how binary search works:

287
00:16:51,615 --> 00:16:53,985
you have an array of values that are in order,

288
00:16:53,985 --> 00:16:58,155
and you have a key, which is the value you're trying to locate within the array.

289
00:16:58,155 --> 00:17:01,158
And you keep track of two variables, which are the lower and upper bounds

290
00:17:01,158 --> 00:17:03,556
of where you think that value could possibly be;

291
00:17:03,556 --> 00:17:05,894
right now, it could be anywhere.

292
00:17:05,894 --> 00:17:08,472
And you look right in the middle of that range -

293
00:17:08,472 --> 00:17:12,568
if what you find is too small, then the key has to be after that.

294
00:17:12,568 --> 00:17:13,971
Look in the middle of the range,

295
00:17:13,971 --> 00:17:16,039
if what you find is too big, the key has to be before that.

296
00:17:16,039 --> 00:17:18,875
And you kind of keep subdividing array into intervals

297
00:17:18,875 --> 00:17:22,178
You narrow in on value you're looking for

298
00:17:22,178 --> 00:17:27,082
And in code, binary search looks like this

299
00:17:27,082 --> 00:17:29,753
And from my perspective, you can't see anything in here

300
00:17:29,753 --> 00:17:34,658
Can't see anything. I see the word array, but I don't actually see an array

301
00:17:34,658 --> 00:17:38,140
And so in order to write code like this, you have to imagine an array in your head

302
00:17:38,140 --> 00:17:40,530
And you essentially have to play computer.

303
00:17:40,530 --> 00:17:45,769
You have to simulate in your head what each line of code would do on a computer

304
00:17:45,769 --> 00:17:48,772
And people that we consider the skilled software engineers

305
00:17:48,772 --> 00:17:52,805
are just those people that are really good at playing computer

306
00:17:52,805 --> 00:17:56,813
But for writing our code on a computer

307
00:17:56,813 --> 00:18:00,750
why are we simulating what a computer would do in our head ?

308
00:18:00,750 --> 00:18:05,390
What isn't the computer just do it and show us ?

309
00:18:05,390 --> 00:18:08,723
So. Let's write binary search.

310
00:18:08,723 --> 00:18:15,432
function binarySearch, takes a key and an array.

311
00:18:15,432 --> 00:18:18,201
And then over here on this side, it's saying

312
00:18:18,201 --> 00:18:21,404
"Ok, it takes a key and an array, such as what?

313
00:18:21,404 --> 00:18:24,074
Give me an example; I need something to work with here."

314
00:18:24,074 --> 00:18:31,114
So, for instance, my array might be 'a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f'.

315
00:18:31,114 --> 00:18:34,723
And let's say for instance we're looking for the 'd'.

316
00:18:34,723 --> 00:18:36,820
So now let's start coding.

317
00:18:36,820 --> 00:18:40,358
The lower bound starts out as zero.

318
00:18:40,358 --> 00:18:43,860
Over here it says 'low = 0', nothing amazing there.

319
00:18:43,860 --> 00:18:50,639
Upper bound starts out at the end of the array, so 'high = array.length - 1'.

320
00:18:50,639 --> 00:18:53,838
And over here, it says 'high = 5'.

321
00:18:53,838 --> 00:18:57,941
So I have my abstract formula in the code.

322
00:18:57,941 --> 00:19:00,710
Over here, it's giving me the concrete value

323
00:19:00,710 --> 00:19:03,747
corresponding to these example arguments.

324
00:19:03,747 --> 00:19:06,889
So I don't have to maintain this picture in my head;

325
00:19:06,889 --> 00:19:09,729
it's just showing it to me.

326
00:19:09,729 --> 00:19:13,023
So now I need the index in the middle of the array,

327
00:19:13,023 --> 00:19:14,859
so I'm going to take the average of those two.

328
00:19:14,859 --> 00:19:22,099
'mid =(low + high)/2', and...well that's obviously not right.

329
00:19:22,099 --> 00:19:27,570
2.5 is not a valid array index. So I guess I need to round this off.

330
00:19:27,570 --> 00:19:30,806
So I'm going to add the floor function and it rounded it down to 2.

331
00:19:30,806 --> 00:19:38,185
And I caught that bug literally the second I typed it, instead of writing an entire function and twenty unit tests.

332
00:19:38,185 --> 00:19:43,153
So now I get the value out of the array...

333
00:19:43,153 --> 00:19:45,855
and then I need to subdivide my range,

334
00:19:45,855 --> 00:19:51,094
which, so this if statement which I'll just paste in here.

335
00:19:51,094 --> 00:19:53,807
So in this case, the value I found is less than the key,

336
00:19:53,807 --> 00:19:56,198
so it's taking this first branch of the if statement.

337
00:19:56,198 --> 00:20:00,004
This is adjusting the lower bound.

338
00:20:00,004 --> 00:20:02,739
Of course if the key was smaller, then

339
00:20:02,739 --> 00:20:06,075
it would take this branch of the if statement and adjust the upper bound.

340
00:20:06,075 --> 00:20:09,178
Or, if the key was 'c', then

341
00:20:09,178 --> 00:20:13,384
we would've just happened to find it on the first shot,  and we'd return the index.

342
00:20:13,384 --> 00:20:19,422
So this is the first iteration of this algorithm.

343
00:20:19,422 --> 00:20:21,492
And now what we need to do, is loop.

344
00:20:21,492 --> 00:20:23,694
We've subdivided the array, we need to keep subdividing

345
00:20:23,694 --> 00:20:27,306
until we narrow in on what we're looking for.

346
00:20:27,306 --> 00:20:30,306
So, we need to loop; I will just loop.

347
00:20:30,306 --> 00:20:35,472
while 1, do all this.

348
00:20:35,472 --> 00:20:38,241
And now what we have are three columns

349
00:20:38,241 --> 00:20:41,911
corresponding to three iterations of this loop.

350
00:20:41,911 --> 00:20:44,747
So this first column here is exactly what you saw before:

351
00:20:44,747 --> 00:20:49,586
low and high span the entire array, we found a 'c', it was too low,

352
00:20:49,586 --> 00:20:52,757
so we adjusted our lower bound, and loop up to here.

353
00:20:52,757 --> 00:20:56,219
Second iteration, bounds are tighter; we found an 'e'.

354
00:20:56,219 --> 00:20:58,095
We adjust the upper bound.

355
00:20:58,095 --> 00:21:01,397
Third iteration, loop up to here; low and high are the same.

356
00:21:01,397 --> 00:21:03,734
We've narrowed it down to a single candidate -

357
00:21:03,734 --> 00:21:05,718
it's indeed the key we're looking for,

358
00:21:05,718 --> 00:21:08,004
and we returned this index.

359
00:21:08,004 --> 00:21:09,240
So there's nothing hidden here;

360
00:21:09,240 --> 00:21:13,545
you see exactly what the algorithm is doing at every point.

361
00:21:13,545 --> 00:21:15,812
And I can go up to here and try different keys,

362
00:21:15,812 --> 00:21:21,253
so I can see how the algorithm behaves for these different input arguments.

363
00:21:21,253 --> 00:21:22,753
And by looking across this data,

364
00:21:22,753 --> 00:21:27,218
I can develop an intuition for how this algorithm works.

365
00:21:27,218 --> 00:21:33,163
So I'm trying different keys here, and say I try looking for a 'g'.

366
00:21:33,163 --> 00:21:37,533
And this looks a little different. It's not actually returning.

367
00:21:37,533 --> 00:21:43,051
And the reason for this is, I'm looking for a key which is not actually in the array.

368
00:21:43,051 --> 00:21:47,410
And the only way of breaking out of this loop, is by finding the key.

369
00:21:47,410 --> 00:21:50,847
So it's kinda stuck here looping forever.

370
00:21:50,847 --> 00:21:53,218
So we can take a look at this and see what went wrong,

371
00:21:53,218 --> 00:21:55,184
where's the algorithm going off the rails.

372
00:21:55,184 --> 00:21:58,219
These first few iterations look fine,

373
00:21:58,219 --> 00:22:00,589
but this iteration looks weird,

374
00:22:00,589 --> 00:22:04,468
because low is greater than high.

375
00:22:04,468 --> 00:22:07,386
Our range is completely collapsed.

376
00:22:07,386 --> 00:22:10,900
So if we get to this point, then we know the key can't be found.

377
00:22:10,900 --> 00:22:16,005
So I see this faulty condition, and I say, "Oh, that's not right; low has to be less than or equal to high."

378
00:22:16,005 --> 00:22:19,075
Okay, well, I'll just put that over as the condition for my while statement.

379
00:22:19,075 --> 00:22:23,801
'low <= high', and then that would break out of the loop,

380
00:22:23,801 --> 00:22:27,550
and I would return some signal to say that it couldn't be found

381
00:22:27,550 --> 00:22:30,753
So here we have 3 iterations 'for loop', couldn't be found

382
00:22:30,753 --> 00:22:33,856
We return the 'not valid' value

383
00:22:33,856 --> 00:22:36,759
So that's what it might be like to write an algorithm without a blindfold on.

384
00:22:36,759 --> 00:22:46,552
[applause]

385
00:22:46,552 --> 00:22:49,673
So I've got this principle, again,

386
00:22:49,673 --> 00:22:52,385
that creators need to be able to see what they doing.

387
00:22:52,385 --> 00:22:54,478
They need this immediate connection with that they're making.

388
00:22:54,478 --> 00:22:58,315
And I've tried to show this principle through three coding examples,

389
00:22:58,315 --> 00:23:00,816
but that's just because this is a software engineering conference,

390
00:23:00,816 --> 00:23:02,786
I thought I was supposed to talk about programming.

391
00:23:02,786 --> 00:23:07,657
But to me, this principle has nothing to do with programming in particular.

392
00:23:07,657 --> 00:23:11,136
It has to do with any type of creation.

393
00:23:11,136 --> 00:23:12,597
So I'd like to show you a couple more demos,

394
00:23:12,597 --> 00:23:17,168
just to show you the breadth of what I have in mind here.

395
00:23:17,168 --> 00:23:22,219
So, to begin with, let's take a look at a different branch of engineering.

396
00:23:22,219 --> 00:23:25,408
So here I have an electronic circuit that I drew.

397
00:23:25,408 --> 00:23:30,508
I'm not quite done drawing it, so let me finish it up there.

398
00:23:32,016 --> 00:23:36,814
Here we'll put 2. And now we have a working circuit.

399
00:23:37,322 --> 00:23:42,218
I mean I assume it's a working circuit. I don't actually see anything working here.

400
00:23:42,218 --> 00:23:46,396
So this is exactly the same as writing code, that we work in a static representation.

401
00:23:46,396 --> 00:23:49,767
But what we actually care about is the data.

402
00:23:49,767 --> 00:23:52,302
The values of the variables, so we can't see that here.

403
00:23:52,302 --> 00:23:57,006
Now in a circuit, the variables are the voltages on these different wires.

404
00:23:57,006 --> 00:24:00,692
So each of these wires has a voltage that's changing over time,

405
00:24:00,692 --> 00:24:03,112
and we have to be able to see that.

406
00:24:03,112 --> 00:24:06,526
Now, if I was building this circuit on a lab bench, building it physically,

407
00:24:06,526 --> 00:24:09,830
I could at least take an oscilloscope and kinda poke around and see

408
00:24:09,830 --> 00:24:11,693
what's going on in the different wires,

409
00:24:11,693 --> 00:24:12,524
what's going on here, or here.

410
00:24:12,524 --> 00:24:16,559
So at the very least, I should be able to do that.

411
00:24:16,559 --> 00:24:21,936
So what I have here, is a plot of the voltage of this wire over time.

412
00:24:21,936 --> 00:24:24,535
You can see it's high, it's low. High.. Low...

413
00:24:24,535 --> 00:24:27,371
So this is clearly oscillating

414
00:24:27,371 --> 00:24:31,307
If I built it physically, also I would be able to see this circuit doing something.

415
00:24:31,307 --> 00:24:34,711
So, in this case I've got these two LEDs up here

416
00:24:34,711 --> 00:24:39,216
These are LEDs, the little lights, presumably there for a reason

417
00:24:39,216 --> 00:24:42,884
I can hit Play and watch it simulate out in real-time

418
00:24:42,884 --> 00:24:51,604
So now you can see what this circuit is doing [applause]

419
00:24:51,604 --> 00:24:53,465
In order to design a circuit like this,

420
00:24:53,465 --> 00:24:56,999
you have to understand the voltage on every wire.

421
00:24:56,999 --> 00:25:00,854
You have to understand how all the voltages are changing throughout the entire circuit.

422
00:25:00,854 --> 00:25:03,037
And just like coding,

423
00:25:03,037 --> 00:25:07,509
either the environment shows that to you, or you simulate it in your head.

424
00:25:07,509 --> 00:25:11,114
And I have better things to do with my head, than simulating what electrons are doing.

425
00:25:11,114 --> 00:25:14,936
So what I'm gonna do, I'm gonna spread it out a bit.

426
00:25:14,936 --> 00:25:18,103
So same circuit, just spread out a little bit,

427
00:25:18,103 --> 00:25:20,687
and I'm going to add the voltage at every node.

428
00:25:20,687 --> 00:25:24,495
So now you can see every voltage throughout the circuit.

429
00:25:24,495 --> 00:25:29,768
And I can even hit Play and watch it all kind of simulate out in real-time.

430
00:25:29,768 --> 00:25:32,902
Although, what I prefer to do is

431
00:25:32,902 --> 00:25:35,071
just move my mouse over it,

432
00:25:35,071 --> 00:25:40,443
and I can kind of look in areas that are interesting to me and see what the values are.

433
00:25:40,443 --> 00:25:42,880
I can compare any two nodes.

434
00:25:42,880 --> 00:25:44,548
So if you look at say the node over here,

435
00:25:44,548 --> 00:25:46,187
while I mouse over this one,

436
00:25:46,187 --> 00:25:49,854
you see the shadow of the one I'm mousing over is overlaid on that.

437
00:25:49,854 --> 00:25:52,989
The shadow of the one I'm mousing over is actually overlaid on all of them.

438
00:25:52,989 --> 00:25:55,291
And so I can compare any two nodes

439
00:25:55,291 --> 00:26:00,029
just by mousing over one of them and looking at the other one.

440
00:26:00,029 --> 00:26:04,103
And again, I can immediately see results of my changes.

441
00:26:04,103 --> 00:26:06,902
So I've got this 70k resistor here.

442
00:26:06,902 --> 00:26:08,770
I want to change its value, I just click and drag it,

443
00:26:08,770 --> 00:26:12,575
and now I see the waveforms changing immediately.

444
00:26:12,575 --> 00:26:14,945
And you'll notice that when I click and drag,

445
00:26:14,945 --> 00:26:19,616
it leaves behind the shadow of the waveform before I started dragging,

446
00:26:19,616 --> 00:26:25,687
so I can compare. I can immediately see the results of my changes.

447
00:26:25,687 --> 00:26:30,105
Two golden rules of information design: show the data, show comparisons.

448
00:26:30,105 --> 00:26:32,194
That's all I'm doing here.

449
00:26:32,194 --> 00:26:33,966
But even this isn't quite good enough.

450
00:26:33,966 --> 00:26:35,965
What we're seeing here are the voltages,

451
00:26:35,965 --> 00:26:40,437
but in electronics there are actually two data types. There is voltage and there is current.

452
00:26:40,437 --> 00:26:42,308
And what we're not seeing is the current,

453
00:26:42,308 --> 00:26:44,706
flowing through each of these components.

454
00:26:44,706 --> 00:26:47,853
And in order to design a circuit, you need to understand both the voltage and the current.

455
00:26:47,853 --> 00:26:50,078
You need to understand the interplay between the two.

456
00:26:50,078 --> 00:26:52,215
That's what analog design is.

457
00:26:52,215 --> 00:26:54,769
So what I'm gonna do is spread these out a little bit more.

458
00:26:54,769 --> 00:26:58,154
And now I'm gonna replace each of these components

459
00:26:58,154 --> 00:27:02,124
with a plot of the current going through it over time.

460
00:27:02,124 --> 00:27:05,328
So each of these blue boxes represents a component.

461
00:27:05,328 --> 00:27:07,231
And you can see which component it is,

462
00:27:07,231 --> 00:27:09,967
because it has a little badge in the corner, a little icon,

463
00:27:09,967 --> 00:27:14,270
but now you can see everything that's going on in the circuit.

464
00:27:14,270 --> 00:27:18,707
You can see how the current changes, you can see how the current and the voltage changes.

465
00:27:18,707 --> 00:27:23,157
There's nothing hidden, there's nothing to simulate in your head.

466
00:27:23,157 --> 00:27:25,948
So what we have here is

467
00:27:25,948 --> 00:27:28,491
a different way of representing the circuit.

468
00:27:28,491 --> 00:27:32,455
Just in general, you could draw any circuit with these blocks

469
00:27:32,455 --> 00:27:34,657
but instead of being made out of little squiggly symbols,

470
00:27:34,657 --> 00:27:36,826
it's made out of data.

471
00:27:36,826 --> 00:27:38,761
And I think it's important to ask:

472
00:27:38,761 --> 00:27:43,834
Why do we have these squiggly symbols in the first place? Why do they exist?

473
00:27:43,834 --> 00:27:47,901
They exist because they're easy to draw with pencil on paper.

474
00:27:47,901 --> 00:27:49,818
This is not paper.

475
00:27:49,818 --> 00:27:52,175
So when you have a new medium, you have to rethink these things.

476
00:27:52,175 --> 00:27:57,613
You have to think how can this new medium allow us to have a more immediate connection

477
00:27:57,613 --> 00:28:02,418
to what we're making. How can this new medium allow us to work in such a way

478
00:28:02,418 --> 00:28:03,985
that we can see what we're doing.

479
00:28:03,985 --> 00:28:06,755
And it's really the same situation with programming.

480
00:28:06,755 --> 00:28:08,524
Our current conception of what a computer program is 

481
00:28:08,524 --> 00:28:10,234
a list of textual definitions that you hand to a compiler.

482
00:28:10,234 --> 00:28:14,263
That's derived straight from Fortran and ALGOL in the late '50's.

483
00:28:14,263 --> 00:28:17,600
Those languages were designed for punchcards.

484
00:28:17,600 --> 00:28:20,536
See, you'd type your program on a stack of cards,

485
00:28:20,536 --> 00:28:24,106
and hand them to the computer operator, (it's the guy in the bottom picture),

486
00:28:24,106 --> 00:28:26,575
and you would come back later.

487
00:28:26,575 --> 00:28:29,317
So there was no such thing as interactivity back then.

488
00:28:29,317 --> 00:28:35,718
And that assumption is baked into our current notions of what programming is.

489
00:28:35,718 --> 00:28:38,088
C was designed for telepipes.

490
00:28:38,088 --> 00:28:41,157
That's Ken Tompson and Dennis Richie up there.

491
00:28:41,157 --> 00:28:43,151
Richie made C.

492
00:28:43,151 --> 00:28:45,734
And there are no video displays in this picture.

493
00:28:45,734 --> 00:28:50,100
Ritchie is basically typing on a fancy typewriter that types back to him.

494
00:28:50,100 --> 00:28:55,972
Any time you use a console or a terminal window, you're emulating a teletype.

495
00:28:55,972 --> 00:28:58,374
And even today, people still think of a REPL

496
00:28:58,374 --> 00:29:02,478
or an interactive top-level as being interactive programming.

497
00:29:02,478 --> 00:29:07,917
Because that's the best thing you could do on a teletype.

498
00:29:07,917 --> 00:29:11,119
So I have one more demo I want to show because I want to emphasize that

499
00:29:11,119 --> 00:29:14,957
this principle, immediate connection, is not even about engineering,

500
00:29:14,957 --> 00:29:17,025
it's about any type of creation.

501
00:29:17,025 --> 00:29:20,163
So I want to move to a different field entirely.

502
00:29:20,163 --> 00:29:23,235
So let's think about animation.

503
00:29:23,235 --> 00:29:26,650
So I've got this painting here, of a tree and leaf on it

504
00:29:26,650 --> 00:29:33,318
and I want to make a little video with the leaf kinda drifting down the tree.

505
00:29:33,318 --> 00:29:37,650
And the normal way of doing this, in a conventional animation package like Flash,

506
00:29:37,650 --> 00:29:40,150
is through keyframes.

507
00:29:40,150 --> 00:29:43,786
So you basically say where you want the leaf to be at different points in time,

508
00:29:43,786 --> 00:29:46,922
and you hit Play and see what it looks like.

509
00:29:46,922 --> 00:29:53,901
So, I'm gonna say: at frame 20, I'm gonna create a keyframe

510
00:29:53,901 --> 00:29:56,567
and the leaf should be there.

511
00:29:56,567 --> 00:30:01,036
At frame 40, create a keyframe and the leaf should be there,

512
00:30:01,036 --> 00:30:04,006
and I'm just totally guessing here. I can not see the motion.

513
00:30:04,006 --> 00:30:05,741
I can not feel the timing,

514
00:30:05,741 --> 00:30:13,568
I'm just throwing things in time and space.

515
00:30:13,568 --> 00:30:15,585
So I've got this leaf at different points in time,

516
00:30:15,585 --> 00:30:20,090
I'm going to add a tween, which tells Flash to connect the dots.

517
00:30:20,090 --> 00:30:24,592
And then I'm gonna hit Play and see what it looks like.

518
00:30:24,592 --> 00:30:33,783
And it looks ridiculous, it looks like billiard balls bouncing back and forth.

519
00:30:33,783 --> 00:30:38,607
And the thing is I kind of know what I want, right ? It's a leaf.

520
00:30:38,607 --> 00:30:41,317
I want leaf drifting down from a tree.

521
00:30:41,317 --> 00:30:46,616
And I can even perform that with my hand: leaf drifting down from a tree.

522
00:30:46,616 --> 00:30:49,352
But Flash doesn't know how to listen to my hand.

523
00:30:49,352 --> 00:30:52,988
But maybe there's a new medium

524
00:30:52,988 --> 00:30:56,759
that does know something about listening to my hand.

525
00:30:56,759 --> 00:30:59,628
So what I'm gonna show you here is a little app I made

526
00:30:59,628 --> 00:31:02,531
for performing animation.

527
00:31:02,531 --> 00:31:05,167
And we're not really set up for doing a live demo off the iPad

528
00:31:05,167 --> 00:31:11,574
so I'm just gonna show you a video of me making a video.

529
00:31:11,574 --> 00:31:13,319
The way this scene is going to play out is

530
00:31:13,319 --> 00:31:15,077
the leaf is gonna kind of drift down from the tree,

531
00:31:15,077 --> 00:31:18,080
and the scene is gonna pan over and the rabbit is gonna do something.

532
00:31:18,080 --> 00:31:21,784
And two things:

533
00:31:21,784 --> 00:31:24,088
one, this is going to move pretty quickly,

534
00:31:24,088 --> 00:31:29,492
and second, I'll be using both hands at almost all times.

535
00:31:29,492 --> 00:31:32,528
So I've got these different layers, the background, the mid-ground and the foreground.

