00:33:12,702 --> 00:33:18,167
And then I find the point when the bunny is about to take off the ground.

565
00:33:18,167 --> 00:33:20,971
Which is right there.

566
00:33:20,971 --> 00:33:25,075
I switch his pose and I kind of toggle between the poses as he hops away.

567
00:33:25,075 --> 00:33:28,411
And then I run it back because I wanna check out how it looked

568
00:33:28,411 --> 00:33:31,015
and I'm just gonna bring that up full screen for you.

569
00:33:31,015 --> 00:33:50,332
This is the piece.

570
00:33:50,332 --> 00:33:54,603
So I made that in 2 minutes, performing with my hands like a musical instrument.

571
00:33:54,603 --> 00:33:58,407
Very immediate connection between me and what I was trying to make.

572
00:33:58,407 --> 00:34:08,252
[applause]

573
00:34:08,252 --> 00:34:10,518
One of the inspirations for this tool

574
00:34:10,518 --> 00:34:14,122
was an animation I tried to make several years ago.

575
00:34:14,122 --> 00:34:18,560
Not that one but it also began with a leaf drifting down from a tree.

576
00:34:18,560 --> 00:34:22,298
And I spent all day in Flash trying to keyframe that leaf.

577
00:34:22,298 --> 00:34:25,812
Couldn't do it.

578
00:34:25,812 --> 00:34:27,727
And so that was the end of that.

579
00:34:27,727 --> 00:34:30,479
I still have my storyboards.

580
00:34:30,479 --> 00:34:32,908
Sometimes I play the music I wrote for the piece.

581
00:34:32,908 --> 00:34:37,477
But the piece itself is locked in my head.

582
00:34:37,477 --> 00:34:40,948
And so I always think about

583
00:34:40,948 --> 00:34:44,729
the millions of pieces that are locked in millions of heads.

584
00:34:44,729 --> 00:34:47,625
And not just animation, and not just art, but

585
00:34:47,625 --> 00:34:50,158
all kinds of ideas.

586
00:34:50,158 --> 00:34:53,836
All kinds of ideas, including critically important ideas,

587
00:34:53,836 --> 00:34:56,765
world changing inventions, life saving scientific discoveries.

588
00:34:56,765 --> 00:35:01,671
These are all ideas that must be grown.

589
00:35:01,671 --> 00:35:04,062
And without an environment in which they can grow,

590
00:35:04,062 --> 00:35:06,842
or their creator can nurture them with this immediate connection,

591
00:35:06,842 --> 00:35:11,014
many of these ideas will not emerge.

592
00:35:11,014 --> 00:35:14,018
Or they'll emerge stunted.

593
00:35:14,018 --> 00:35:18,321
So I have this principle that creators need an immediate connection, and

594
00:35:18,321 --> 00:35:23,827
all of these demos that I just showed you simply came from me looking around,

595
00:35:23,827 --> 00:35:27,228
noticing places where this principle was violated,

596
00:35:27,228 --> 00:35:29,229
and then trying to fix that.

597
00:35:29,229 --> 00:35:31,144
It's really all I did.

598
00:35:31,144 --> 00:35:34,069
I just followed this guiding principle

599
00:35:34,069 --> 00:35:41,244
and it guided me to what I had to do.

600
00:35:41,244 --> 00:35:46,348
But I haven't said much about the most important part of the story, which is Why.

601
00:35:46,348 --> 00:35:52,419
Why I have this principle. Why I do this.

602
00:35:52,419 --> 00:35:58,928
When I see a violation of this principle, I don't think of that as an opportunity.

603
00:35:58,928 --> 00:36:03,832
When I see creators constrained by their tools, their ideas compromised,

604
00:36:03,832 --> 00:36:07,070
I don't say: Oh good, an opportunity to make a product.

605
00:36:07,070 --> 00:36:10,038
An opportunity to start a business.

606
00:36:10,038 --> 00:36:14,878
Or an opportunity to do research or contribute to a field.

607
00:36:14,878 --> 00:36:17,146
I'm not excited by finding a problem to solve.

608
00:36:17,146 --> 00:36:20,883
I'm not in this for the joy of making things.

609
00:36:20,883 --> 00:36:23,100
Ideas are very precious to me.

610
00:36:23,100 --> 00:36:27,690
And when I see ideas dying, it hurts.

611
00:36:27,690 --> 00:36:31,598
I see a tragedy.

612
00:36:31,598 --> 00:36:34,845
To me it feels like a moral wrong, it feels like an injustice.

613
00:36:34,845 --> 00:36:37,166
And if I think there's anything I can do about it,

614
00:36:37,166 --> 00:36:40,536
I feel it's my responsibility to do so.

615
00:36:40,536 --> 00:36:44,874
Not opportunity, but responsibility.

616
00:36:44,874 --> 00:36:48,262
Now this is just my thing. I'm not asking you to believe in this the way I believe I do.

617
00:36:48,262 --> 00:36:51,880
My point here is that these words that I'm using:

618
00:36:51,880 --> 00:36:57,489
Injustice, Responsibility, Moral wrong,

619
00:36:57,489 --> 00:37:02,124
these aren't the words we normally hear in a technical field.

620
00:37:02,124 --> 00:37:05,430
We do hear these words in association with social causes.

621
00:37:05,430 --> 00:37:06,762
So things like

622
00:37:06,762 --> 00:37:10,632
censorship, gender discrimination, environmental destruction.

623
00:37:10,632 --> 00:37:15,538
We all recognize these things as moral wrongs.

624
00:37:15,538 --> 00:37:19,876
Most of us wouldn't witness a civil rights violation and think "Oh good, an opportunity."

625
00:37:19,876 --> 00:37:21,946
I hope not.

626
00:37:21,946 --> 00:37:25,596
Instead, we've been very fortunate to have people throughout history

627
00:37:25,596 --> 00:37:28,617
who recognized these moral wrongs

628
00:37:28,617 --> 00:37:32,154
and saw it as their responsibility to address them.

629
00:37:32,154 --> 00:37:34,223
And so there's this activist lifestyle where

630
00:37:34,223 --> 00:37:36,763
a person dedicates themselves

631
00:37:36,763 --> 00:37:40,895
to fighting for a cause that they believe in.

632
00:37:40,895 --> 00:37:45,069
And the purpose of this talk is to tell you that

633
00:37:45,069 --> 00:37:48,972
this activist lifestyle is not just for social activism.

634
00:37:48,972 --> 00:37:53,014
As a technologist, you can recognize a wrong in the world.

635
00:37:53,014 --> 00:37:55,878
You can have a vision of what a better world could be.

636
00:37:55,878 --> 00:38:00,181
And you can dedicate yourself to fighting for a principle.

637
00:38:00,181 --> 00:38:02,097
Socially activists typically fight by organizing

638
00:38:02,097 --> 00:38:07,690
but you can fight by inventing.

639
00:38:07,690 --> 00:38:12,462
So now I'd like to tell you about a few other people who have lived this way,

640
00:38:12,462 --> 00:38:15,930
starting with Larry Tesler.

641
00:38:15,930 --> 00:38:19,013
Larry has done a lot of wonderful things in his life,

642
00:38:19,013 --> 00:38:23,205
but the work I'm gonna tell you about he did in the mid '70s at Xerox PARC.

643
00:38:23,205 --> 00:38:27,513
And at the time, there really wasn't such a thing as personal computers.

644
00:38:27,513 --> 00:38:29,913
The notion of personal computing was very young and

645
00:38:29,913 --> 00:38:33,650
Larry and colleagues at PARC felt that they had transformative potential,

646
00:38:33,650 --> 00:38:39,929
that personal computing could change how people thought and lived.

647
00:38:39,929 --> 00:38:43,324
And I think all of us in this room would agree that they turned out to be right about that.

648
00:38:43,324 --> 00:38:45,263
But at the time,

649
00:38:45,263 --> 00:38:49,165
software interfaces were designed around modes.

650
00:38:49,165 --> 00:38:53,870
So, in a text editor for instance, you couldn't just type

651
00:38:53,870 --> 00:38:56,429
and have words appear on the screen like on a typewriter.

652
00:38:56,429 --> 00:38:57,873
You would be in command mode.

653
00:38:57,873 --> 00:39:01,189
If you wanted to insert text you'd have to press I to go into insert mode

654
00:39:01,189 --> 00:39:04,279
then Escape back out to command mode or maybe you'd hit A to go into append mode.

655
00:39:04,279 --> 00:39:06,714
Or if you wanted to move text around you'd hit M go to the Move mode

656
00:39:06,714 --> 00:39:09,053
and then you'd have to select and move things around

657
00:39:09,053 --> 00:39:16,157
And Larry would watch people using the computer,

658
00:39:16,157 --> 00:39:20,895
they actually pioneered the concept of software user studies, another thing that he did,

659
00:39:20,895 --> 00:39:24,431
but he would watch people using the software and he found that many people

660
00:39:24,431 --> 00:39:27,535
even after training and weeks of use,

661
00:39:27,535 --> 00:39:31,012
many people would not become comfortable with the computer.

662
00:39:31,012 --> 00:39:35,210
And he believed that it was these modes that were to blame.

663
00:39:35,210 --> 00:39:37,509
That the complexity of modes

664
00:39:37,509 --> 00:39:41,009
was a kind of barrier that many people couldn't cross.

665
00:39:41,009 --> 00:39:46,105
And so this kind of represented a threat

666
00:39:46,105 --> 00:39:49,590
to this dream of what personal computing could be.

667
00:39:49,590 --> 00:39:52,995
So Larry made it his personal mission to eliminate modes from software.

668
00:39:52,995 --> 00:39:54,696
And he formed a principle:

669
00:39:54,696 --> 00:39:58,300
"No person should be trapped in a mode"

670
00:39:58,300 --> 00:39:59,902
His slogan that he would go around saying was

671
00:39:59,902 --> 00:40:04,406
"Don't mode me in" and he had it printed on his t-shirt.

672
00:40:04,406 --> 00:40:07,309
And this principle informed everything that he did.

673
00:40:07,309 --> 00:40:09,478
He thought about it with all the work that he did.

674
00:40:09,478 --> 00:40:13,426
And eventually he came up with a text editor called Gypsy,

675
00:40:13,426 --> 00:40:17,052
which essentially introduced text editing as we know today.

676
00:40:17,052 --> 00:40:19,090
There's an insertion point.

677
00:40:19,090 --> 00:40:22,891
And when you typed, words appeared on the screen.

678
00:40:22,891 --> 00:40:26,424
To select text, he invented modeless selection with click and drag.

679
00:40:26,424 --> 00:40:30,865
So you just click and drag over the text you want to select like using a highlighter,

680
00:40:30,865 --> 00:40:33,168
one of the first uses of drag.

681
00:40:33,168 --> 00:40:36,138
To move text around, he invented these commands that he called

682
00:40:36,138 --> 00:40:38,238
Cut, Copy, Paste

683
00:40:38,238 --> 00:40:42,045
So you select and Cut, later on you Paste in, whenever you're ready

684
00:40:42,045 --> 00:40:45,112
You're never trapped in a mode, you don't have the switching between modes

685
00:40:45,112 --> 00:40:49,920
When you hit the 'W' key on a keyboard, you get 'W' on the screen, always.

686
00:40:49,920 --> 00:40:53,258
And he would watch people using his software

687
00:40:53,258 --> 00:40:55,691
and he found that someone who had never seen a computer before,

688
00:40:55,691 --> 00:40:57,727
which was most people back then, 

689
00:40:57,727 --> 00:41:00,829
could be up and running in like half an hour.

690
00:41:00,829 --> 00:41:02,931
So this was clearly a transformative change

691
00:41:02,931 --> 00:41:05,843
in enabling people to connect with computers.

692
00:41:05,843 --> 00:41:09,303
And his ideas about modelessness

693
00:41:09,303 --> 00:41:11,925
spread to the rest of the desktop interface

694
00:41:11,925 --> 00:41:13,840
which was then being invented at Xeroc PARC at the same time.

695
00:41:13,840 --> 00:41:20,816
And today they're so ingrained in the computing experience that today we kind of take them for granted.

696
00:41:20,816 --> 00:41:26,321
Now I said that Larry made the elimination of modes his personal mission.

697
00:41:26,321 --> 00:41:30,126
That's actually his words, and if you think he's exaggerating,

698
00:41:30,126 --> 00:41:37,364
here's Larry's license plate for the last 30 years. [chuckles]

699
00:41:37,364 --> 00:41:41,871
Nowadays of course Larry has a website, at nomodes.com

700
00:41:41,871 --> 00:41:46,408
and he's on twitter: @nomodes

701
00:41:46,408 --> 00:41:49,879
And so like I said, Larry has done a lot of amazing work in his career

702
00:41:49,879 --> 00:41:57,386
but his self identity is clearly associated with this cause.

703
00:41:57,386 --> 00:41:58,591
And so I'd like to ask

704
00:41:58,591 --> 00:42:02,190
What exactly did Larry do?

705
00:42:02,190 --> 00:42:06,862
Like how could we best describe what Larry did?

706
00:42:06,862 --> 00:42:09,765
A typical biography might say:

707
00:42:09,765 --> 00:42:13,182
Larry Tesler invented Cut Copy Paste.

708
00:42:13,182 --> 00:42:16,706
Which is true, but I think it's really misleading, because

709
00:42:16,706 --> 00:42:19,840
this invention was very different than

710
00:42:19,840 --> 00:42:23,508
say, Thomas Edison inventing the phonograph.

711
00:42:23,508 --> 00:42:26,516
Edison basically just stumbled over the technology for audio recording

712
00:42:26,516 --> 00:42:28,917
and he built it out as a novelly.

713
00:42:28,917 --> 00:42:33,187
And he came up with like a this list of possible applications for his technology, but

714
00:42:33,187 --> 00:42:35,891
he didn't have any cultural intent.

715
00:42:35,891 --> 00:42:38,425
Whereas what Larry did was entirely a reaction

716
00:42:38,425 --> 00:42:41,926
to a particular cultural context.

717
00:42:41,926 --> 00:42:44,099
So another thing that you might hear is that

718
00:42:44,099 --> 00:42:48,603
Larry Tesler solved the problem of modeless text manipulation.

719
00:42:48,603 --> 00:42:51,541
Solved the problem. And obviously that's true,

720
00:42:51,541 --> 00:42:55,310
he worked on the problem for a long time, eventually solved it.

721
00:42:55,310 --> 00:42:58,176
But I think that's misleading too,

722
00:42:58,176 --> 00:43:03,617
because this problem that he solved only existed in his own head.

723
00:43:03,617 --> 00:43:07,622
Nobody else saw this as a problem.

724
00:43:07,622 --> 00:43:11,127
For everybody else modes were just how computers worked.

725
00:43:11,127 --> 00:43:13,496
There wasn't anything wrong with them any more than

726
00:43:13,496 --> 00:43:15,399
we think there's something wrong with having two arms.

727
00:43:15,399 --> 00:43:18,340
It just kind of was a fact of life.

728
00:43:18,340 --> 00:43:20,508
So the first thing that Larry did

729
00:43:20,508 --> 00:43:26,925
was that he recognized a wrong that had been unacknowledged in the culture.

730
00:43:26,925 --> 00:43:31,647
And the thing is, that's how many great social changes began as well.

731
00:43:31,647 --> 00:43:35,887
So a 150 years ago, Elizabeth Cady Stanton had to stand up and say:

732
00:43:35,887 --> 00:43:37,887
"Women should vote."

733
00:43:37,887 --> 00:43:40,919
And everybody else said like "That's crazy, what are you talking about ?"

734
00:43:40,919 --> 00:43:44,359
Today, we recognize gender discrimination as a wrong.

735
00:43:44,359 --> 00:43:48,865
Back then, it was part of society, it was invisible.

736
00:43:48,865 --> 00:43:52,198
She had to recognize it, and she had to fight it.

737
00:43:52,198 --> 00:43:56,585
And to me, that's a much closer model to what Larry did

738
00:43:56,585 --> 00:44:01,419
than the Thomas Edison model of inventing a bunch of random technology so he could patent it.

739
00:44:01,419 --> 00:44:03,086
Now to be clear I'm not making any judgement

740
00:44:03,086 --> 00:44:05,513
about the relative importance or the impact of these two people,

741
00:44:05,513 --> 00:44:09,834
I'm just talking about their motivations and their approach.

742
00:44:09,834 --> 00:44:13,023
Both of them recognized a cultural wrong,

743
00:44:13,023 --> 00:44:15,757
they envisioned a world without that wrong

744
00:44:15,757 --> 00:44:19,586
and they dedicated themselves to fighting for a principle.

745
00:44:19,586 --> 00:44:23,668
She fought by organizing, he fought by inventing.

746
00:44:23,668 --> 00:44:28,036
And many other seminal figures in computing had similar motivations.

747
00:44:28,036 --> 00:44:30,374
So certainly Doug Engelbart.

748
00:44:30,374 --> 00:44:34,752
Doug Engelbart basically invented interactive computing.

749
00:44:34,752 --> 00:44:38,545
The concept of putting information on a screen.

750
00:44:38,545 --> 00:44:40,181
Navigating through it.

751
00:44:40,181 --> 00:44:41,920
Looking at information in different ways.

752
00:44:41,920 --> 00:44:45,788
Pointing at things and manipulating them. He came up with all this at a time when

753
00:44:45,788 --> 00:44:49,524
real-time interaction with a computer was just almost unheard of.

754
00:44:49,524 --> 00:44:51,459
Today he is best known as the inventor of the mouse,

755
00:44:51,459 --> 00:44:55,597
but what he really invented with is this entirely new way of working with knowledge.

756
00:44:55,597 --> 00:44:58,599
His explicit goal from the beginning was

757
00:44:58,599 --> 00:45:02,772
to enable mankind to solve the world's urgent problems.

758
00:45:02,772 --> 00:45:04,502
And his vision,

759
00:45:04,502 --> 00:45:07,042
he had this this vision of what he called knowledge workers

760
00:45:07,042 --> 00:45:12,347
using complex powerful information tools to harness the collective intelligence.

761
00:45:12,347 --> 00:45:16,117
And he only got into computers because he had a hunch that these new things called computer things

762
00:45:16,117 --> 00:45:18,585
could help him realize that vision.

763
00:45:18,585 --> 00:45:20,419
Everything that he did

764
00:45:20,419 --> 00:45:26,761
was almost single-mindedly driven by pursuing this vision.

765
00:45:26,761 --> 00:45:28,585
Here's Alan Kay.

766
00:45:28,585 --> 00:45:32,085
Alan Kay ran the lab at Xerox PARC where we got the desktop interface,

767
00:45:32,085 --> 00:45:35,637
so things like windows and icons, command menus.

768
00:45:35,637 --> 00:45:40,375
He also invented object-oriented programming and lots of other things.

769
00:45:40,375 --> 00:45:42,308
His goal, and I quote,

770
00:45:42,308 --> 00:45:44,779
was to "amplify human reach,

771
00:45:44,779 --> 00:45:47,549
and bring new ways of thinking to a faltering civilization

772
00:45:47,549 --> 00:45:49,783
that desperately needed it."

773
00:45:49,783 --> 00:45:51,994
Isn't that great?

774
00:45:51,994 --> 00:45:54,751
His approach was through children. He believed that

775
00:45:54,751 --> 00:45:58,920
if children became fluent in thinking in the medium of the computer,

776
00:45:58,920 --> 00:46:03,835
meaning if programming was a form of basic literacy like reading and writing,

777
00:46:03,835 --> 00:46:06,166
then they'd become adults with new forms of critical thought,

778
00:46:06,166 --> 00:46:07,769
and new ways of understanding the world.

779
00:46:07,769 --> 00:46:10,639
And we'd have this more enlightened society,

780
00:46:10,639 --> 00:46:16,836
similar to the difference that literacy brought to society.

781
00:46:16,836 --> 00:46:19,682
And everything that he did, everything he invented,

782
00:46:19,682 --> 00:46:25,006
came out of pursuing this vision, this goal with children.

783
00:46:25,006 --> 00:46:29,918
And following principles that he adopted from Piaget and Montessori,

784
00:46:29,918 --> 00:46:36,836
Jerome Bruner, these people who would study how children think

785
00:46:36,836 --> 00:46:40,584
And the figure probably most widely associated with software activism

786
00:46:40,584 --> 00:46:43,204
is Richard Stallman.

787
00:46:43,204 --> 00:46:47,175
Stallman started the GNU project which today makes up a big chunk of any Linux system.

788
00:46:47,175 --> 00:46:49,477
He also started the Free Software Foundation,

789
00:46:49,477 --> 00:46:53,348
wrote GCC, GPL, many, many other things.

790
00:46:53,348 --> 00:46:57,053
His principle is that software must be free, as in freedom,

791
00:46:57,053 --> 00:47:01,390
and he has very precise meaning associated with that statement.

792
00:47:01,390 --> 00:47:02,673
He's always been very clear that

793
00:47:02,673 --> 00:47:05,225
software freedom is a matter of moral right and wrong.

794
00:47:05,225 --> 00:47:10,865
And he has taken a particularly uncompromising approach in his own life to that.

795
00:47:10,865 --> 00:47:13,402
All of these tremendously influential people

796
00:47:13,402 --> 00:47:16,205
dedicated their lives

797
00:47:16,205 --> 00:47:20,910
to fighting for a particular ideal with a very clear sense of right and wrong.

798
00:47:20,910 --> 00:47:22,758
Often really fighting

799
00:47:22,758 --> 00:47:26,615
against an authority or mainstream that did not recognize their wrong as being wrong.

800
00:47:26,615 --> 00:47:30,335
And today, the world is still very far from any of their ideals

801
00:47:30,335 --> 00:47:32,504
and so they still see a world in crisis

802
00:47:32,504 --> 00:47:41,096
and they keep fighting. They're always fighting.

803
00:47:41,096 --> 00:47:45,135
Now I'm not saying you have to live this way.

804
00:47:45,135 --> 00:47:48,002
I'm not saying that you should live this way.

805
00:47:48,002 --> 00:47:50,506
What I'm saying is that you can.

806
00:47:50,506 --> 00:47:53,174
That this lifestyle is an option that is available to you.

807
00:47:53,174 --> 00:47:55,414
And it's not one you're gonna hear about much.

808
00:47:55,414 --> 00:47:57,248
Your career counselor is not going to come back to you and say:

809
00:47:57,248 --> 00:47:59,681
"You should start a personal crusade."

810
00:47:59,681 --> 00:48:04,186
In a social field, they might, but not in technology.

811
00:48:04,186 --> 00:48:09,757
Instead the world will try to make you define yourself by a skill.

812
00:48:09,757 --> 00:48:12,227
That's why you have a major in college.

813
00:48:12,227 --> 00:48:13,498
That's why you have a job title.

814
00:48:13,498 --> 00:48:16,265
You are a software engineer.

815
00:48:16,265 --> 00:48:18,663
And you'll probably specialize to be a database engineer

816
00:48:18,663 --> 00:48:20,580
or a front-end engineer,

817
00:48:20,580 --> 00:48:23,238
and you'll be given front-ends and asked to engineer them.

818
00:48:23,238 --> 00:48:26,175
And that could be worthwhile and valuable,

819
00:48:26,175 --> 00:48:32,347
and if you want to spend your life pursuing excellence and practicing a skill,

820
00:48:32,347 --> 00:48:35,016
you can do that. That is the path of a craftsman.

821
00:48:35,016 --> 00:48:37,299
That is the most common path.

822
00:48:37,299 --> 00:48:40,498
The only other path you really hear about much is the path of the problem solver.

823
00:48:40,498 --> 00:48:45,093
So I see entrepreneurship and academic research as kind of two sides of that coin.

824
00:48:45,093 --> 00:48:46,896
There is the field.

825
00:48:46,896 --> 00:48:50,566
There's the set of problems in that field, or needs in the market.

826
00:48:50,566 --> 00:48:53,936
You go in, you choose one, you work it, you make your contribution there.

827
00:48:53,936 --> 00:48:58,807
Maybe later on, you choose another problem, you work it, you make your contribution there.

828
00:48:58,807 --> 00:49:02,710
Again, that could be worthwhile and valuable and if that's what you want to do,

829
00:49:02,710 --> 00:49:04,946
then you can take that path.

830
00:49:04,946 --> 00:49:08,997
But I don't see Larry Tesler on either of those paths.

831
00:49:08,997 --> 00:49:12,620
I wouldn't say he was contributing to the field of user experience design

832
00:49:12,620 --> 00:49:14,888
because there was no such thing.

833
00:49:14,888 --> 00:49:16,891
He didn't choose some open problem to solve,

834
00:49:16,891 --> 00:49:19,664
he came up with some problem that only existed in his own head,

835
00:49:19,664 --> 00:49:21,829
and no one else even recognized.

836
00:49:21,829 --> 00:49:24,766
And certainly he did not define himself by his craft,

837
00:49:24,766 --> 00:49:27,770
he defined himself by his cause.

838
00:49:27,770 --> 00:49:31,371
By the principle he fought to uphold.

839
00:49:31,371 --> 00:49:33,508
And I'm sure if you look at Wikipedia it will say that

840
00:49:33,508 --> 00:49:37,812
he's a computer scientist or a user experience something,

841
00:49:37,812 --> 00:49:41,746
but to me that's like saying Elizabeth Cady Stanton was a community organizer.

842
00:49:41,746 --> 00:49:45,454
No, Elizabeth Cady Stanton established the principle

843
00:49:45,454 --> 00:49:48,288
of women's suffrage. That's who she was.

844
00:49:48,288 --> 00:49:50,558
That was the identity she chose

845
00:49:50,558 --> 00:49:54,529
and Larry Tesler established the principle of modelessness.

846
00:49:54,529 --> 00:50:02,470
He had a vision, and he brought the world to that vision.

847
00:50:02,470 --> 00:50:05,248
So, you can choose this life.

848
00:50:05,248 --> 00:50:07,374
Or maybe it will end up choosing you.

849
00:50:07,374 --> 00:50:09,477
It might not happen right away.

850
00:50:09,477 --> 00:50:12,247
It can take time to find a principle, because

851
00:50:12,247 --> 00:50:14,783
finding a principle is essentially a form of self-discovery,

852
00:50:14,783 --> 00:50:18,187
that you're trying to figure out what your life is supposed to be about.

853
00:50:18,187 --> 00:50:21,722
What you want to stand for as a person.

854
00:50:21,722 --> 00:50:24,626
Took me like a decade.

855
00:50:24,626 --> 00:50:28,631
Ten years before any real understanding of my principles solidified.

856
00:50:28,631 --> 00:50:30,132
That was my twenties.

857
00:50:30,132 --> 00:50:32,977
When I was young I felt I had to live this way

858
00:50:32,977 --> 00:50:36,271
but I would get little glimmers of what mattered to me

859
00:50:36,271 --> 00:50:38,940
but no big picture. It was really unclear.

860
00:50:38,940 --> 00:50:42,043
This was very distressing for me.

861
00:50:42,043 --> 00:50:45,848
What I had to do was just do a lot of things.

862
00:50:45,848 --> 00:50:48,649
Make many things, make many types of things.

863
00:50:48,649 --> 00:50:52,453
Study many things, experience many many things.

864
00:50:52,453 --> 00:50:56,356
And use all these experiences as ways of analyzing myself.

865
00:50:56,356 --> 00:50:58,460
Taking all these experiences and saying:

866
00:50:58,460 --> 00:51:00,361
"Does this resonate with me?"

867
00:51:00,361 --> 00:51:02,996
Does this repel me? Do I not care?

868
00:51:02,996 --> 00:51:07,747
Building of this corpus of experiences that I felt very strongly about for some reason

869
00:51:07,747 --> 00:51:10,072
and trying to make sense of it. Trying to figure out Why?

870
00:51:10,072 --> 00:51:15,611
What is this secret ingredient that I'm reacting to so strongly ?

871
00:51:15,611 --> 00:51:17,445
Now I think everyone's different.

872
00:51:17,445 --> 00:51:20,181
And all the guys I talked about they have their own origin stories

873
00:51:20,181 --> 00:51:22,464
which you can read about.

874
00:51:22,464 --> 00:51:24,252
I will just say that

875
00:51:24,252 --> 00:51:26,954
confining yourself to practicing a single skill

876
00:51:26,954 --> 00:51:30,591
can make it difficult to get that broad range of experiences, which

877
00:51:30,591 --> 00:51:36,830
seem to be so valuable for this sort of work.

878
00:51:36,830 --> 00:51:39,499
And finally,

879
00:51:39,499 --> 00:51:42,904
if you choose to follow a principle,

880
00:51:42,904 --> 00:51:45,841
a principle can't be just any old thing you believe in.

881
00:51:45,841 --> 00:51:49,143
You'll hear a lot of people say they want to make software easier to use.

882
00:51:49,143 --> 00:51:51,214
Or they want to delight their users.

883
00:51:51,214 --> 00:51:53,081
Or they want to make things simple.

884
00:51:53,081 --> 00:51:55,952
That's a really big one right now. Everyone wants to make things simple.

885
00:51:55,952 --> 00:51:58,452
And those are nice thoughts

886
00:51:58,452 --> 00:52:01,022
and maybe kind of give you a direction to go in

887
00:52:01,022 --> 00:52:05,075
but they're too vague to be directly actionable.

888
00:52:05,075 --> 00:52:06,909
Larry Tesler likes simplicity.

889
00:52:06,909 --> 00:52:09,765
But his principle was this specific nugget of insight:

890
00:52:09,765 --> 00:52:11,767
No person should be trapped in a mode.

891
00:52:11,767 --> 00:52:14,168
And that is a powerful principle

892
00:52:14,168 --> 00:52:17,372
because it gave him a new way of seeing the world.

893
00:52:17,372 --> 00:52:20,541
It divided the world in right and wrong in a fairly objective way.

894
00:52:20,541 --> 00:52:25,246
So, he could look at someone selecting text and ask Is this person in a mode?

895
00:52:25,246 --> 00:52:27,157
Yes or no?

896
00:52:27,157 --> 00:52:30,618
If Yes, he had to do something about that.

897
00:52:30,618 --> 00:52:34,957
And likewise, I believe that creators need powerful tools.

898
00:52:34,957 --> 00:52:38,359
It's a nice thought, but it doesn't really get me anywhere.

899
00:52:38,359 --> 00:52:41,963
My principle is that creators need this immediate connection.

900
00:52:41,963 --> 00:52:45,099
So I can watch you changing a line of code, and I can ask:

901
00:52:45,099 --> 00:52:49,240
"Did you immediately see the effect of that change ?" Yes or no.

902
00:52:49,240 --> 00:52:53,207
If No, I got to do something about that.

903
00:52:53,207 --> 00:52:56,242
And again, all those demos that I showed you

904
00:52:56,242 --> 00:52:59,046
came out of me doing that,

905
00:52:59,046 --> 00:53:01,116
of me following this principle

906
00:53:01,116 --> 00:53:04,018
and letting it lead me to exactly what I needed to do.

907
00:53:04,018 --> 00:53:07,158
So if your guiding principle embodies a specific insight,

908
00:53:07,158 --> 00:53:10,491
it will guide you.

909
00:53:10,491 --> 00:53:19,935
And you will always know if what you're doing is right.

910
00:53:19,935 --> 00:53:22,824
There are many ways of living your life.

911
00:53:22,824 --> 00:53:24,871
That's maybe the most important thing you can realize in your life,

912
00:53:24,871 --> 00:53:28,777
is that every aspect of your life is a choice.

913
00:53:28,777 --> 00:53:31,646
But there are default choices.

914
00:53:31,646 --> 00:53:33,681
You can choose to sleepwalk through your life

915
00:53:33,681 --> 00:53:36,552
and accept that path that's been laid out for you.

916
00:53:36,552 --> 00:53:40,055
You can choose to accept the world as it is.

917
00:53:40,055 --> 00:53:42,956
But you don't have to.

918
00:53:42,956 --> 00:53:46,127
If there is something in the world you feel is a wrong

919
00:53:46,127 --> 00:53:49,930
and you have a vision for what a better world could be,

920
00:53:49,930 --> 00:53:52,834
you can find your guiding principle.

921
00:53:52,834 --> 00:53:56,170
And you can fight for a cause.

922
00:53:56,170 --> 00:53:59,307
So after this talk, I'd like you to take a little time and think about

923
00:53:59,307 --> 00:54:01,574
what matters to you.

924
00:54:01,574 --> 00:54:03,993
What you believe in.

925
00:54:03,993 --> 00:54:06,824
And what you might fight for.

926
00:54:06,824 --> 00:54:10,824
Thank you. [applause]

